The neerest to our life and bodie is e verie ones severall mate in wedlocke: For by wedlock two bodies are joy ned together, and are made one. For the Lord said: And two shall be one flesh. In this thirde precept therefore which is next after the forbidding of murther, commaun dement is given for the holie keeping of honourable wedlocke, and for the true sactifying of ye bodie, against ad ulteries, wandering lusts, and al in continencie. Wedlocke is prepared to this end and purpose, that honestie & chastitie may flourish among good me, and children may be brought up in the feare of the Lord. This commaunde ment againe is briefly expressed in as fewe wordes as may be: Thou shalt not commit adulterie. In the exposi tion of this commaundement by the helpe of Gods good spirite, I will first speake of holy matrimonie, then of a dulterie: thirdly I will shew you what is conteined under the name of adul terie: and lastly I will make an ende with a treatise of continencie. Wedlocke, which is also called ma trimonie, is an alliaunce of holy joy ning together of man & woman, cou pled and brought into one by mutuall cosent of them both, to the intent that they using all thinges in common be twixt themselves may live in chasti tie, and traine up their children in the
feare of the Lord. The Gospel verilie
calleth wedlock a joyning together,
which god hath made. for Christ said:
What god hath joyned together, let
no man separate. Neither is it lawful
to make any other the author of ma
trimonie, than God himselfe. God did
by the meane and ministery of his An
gels and chosen men, appoint other
good and necessarie ordinaunces for
mankinds commoditie, but he himself
did immediately without the ministe
rie of any person ordeine matrimonie,
he himselfe did establish and ratifie it
with lawes for the purpose, he himself
did couple the first married folkes, and
hee being the true high priest in deede,
did himselfe blesse the couple then,
whom hee did joyne together.
By this wee may easilie gather the
excellent dignitie of marriage or ma
trimonie. For God did ordeine it, yea
he ordeined it in Paradise, when man
as yet was free from all kinde of cala
mities. Adam when hee was in the
great felicitie of Paradise, seemed not
yet to live commodiously nor sweetely
enough, except a wife were given to
be joyned unto him. It is not good
(sayth God) for man to be alone, I will
make him a helper to tarie or dwell
with him. For God brought to Adam
al living creatures which he had crea
ted for him to name them: but among
them all, there was nothing that A
dam had lust unto, his minde and na
ture did utterly abhore to be coupled
